He's got seniority.

590
00:37:31,600 --> 00:37:35,196
Bill cleans his gun
with bubble bath.

591
00:37:35,280 --> 00:37:36,600
No, it'll be you...

592
00:37:36,680 --> 00:37:38,637
if you want.

593
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:49,435
When you talk to the
police, just keep it simple.

594
00:37:49,520 --> 00:37:51,591
Thanks but no thanks,
in other words.

595
00:37:51,680 --> 00:37:53,114
I've already
talked to Fargo,

596
00:37:53,200 --> 00:37:54,759
and they want to
deal with this themselves.

597
00:37:55,520 --> 00:37:56,954
They're sending guys.

598
00:37:57,040 --> 00:37:58,554
Deal with what?

599
00:37:58,640 --> 00:38:01,394
He was in a whorehouse.

600
00:38:01,480 --> 00:38:02,880
I'm glad he's dead.

601
00:38:02,960 --> 00:38:04,474
Ma, don't talk like that.

602
00:38:04,560 --> 00:38:06,677
Yeah,
Ma, don't talk like that.

603
00:38:06,760 --> 00:38:08,672
Makes me live in the North Pole,

604
00:38:08,760 --> 00:38:11,229
and then he's got the nerve to...

605
00:38:11,320 --> 00:38:13,630
I'm not kidding.

606
00:38:13,720 --> 00:38:15,951
I'm gonna sing at his funeral.

607
00:38:17,520 --> 00:38:18,510
Mmm-hmm.

608
00:38:33,400 --> 00:38:35,790
Mr. Mickey,
you have a phone call.

609
00:38:37,680 --> 00:38:40,070
She said me, you doofus.

610
00:38:40,960 --> 00:38:42,633
Can I come?
No.

611
00:38:42,720 --> 00:38:45,758
Jeez! Just stay
here with Ma.

612
00:38:49,080 --> 00:38:50,878
Hello.
<i>Mickey?</i>

613
00:38:50,960 --> 00:38:54,158
Louis Grossman,
your dad's estate attorney.

614
00:38:54,240 --> 00:38:55,230
First of all...

615
00:38:56,360 --> 00:38:59,114
I'd like to say
how sorry I am for your loss.

616
00:38:59,200 --> 00:39:00,873
Okay.

617
00:39:00,960 --> 00:39:03,191
<i>Next thing is...</i>

618
00:39:03,280 --> 00:39:06,000
I'm responsible for
overseeing the dispersal

619
00:39:06,080 --> 00:39:08,470
of your dad's vast estate.

620
00:39:10,400 --> 00:39:11,550
You mean the money?

621
00:39:11,640 --> 00:39:12,756
<i>Right.</i>

622
00:39:12,840 --> 00:39:18,837
Money, real estate, holdings,
automobiles and...

623
00:39:18,960 --> 00:39:22,032
Well, there's no delicate
way to put this.

624
00:39:22,120 --> 00:39:25,318
The will was very clear.

625
00:39:25,400 --> 00:39:29,030
Your dad decided to give everything 
to your younger brother Moe.

626
00:39:29,120 --> 00:39:30,349
Are you kidding?

627
00:39:30,440 --> 00:39:31,760
<i>I know it's hard to hear...</i>

628
00:39:31,840 --> 00:39:35,470
but the will was very specific.

629
00:39:35,600 --> 00:39:39,719
Quote, I leave the entirety of
my vast estate

630
00:39:39,800 --> 00:39:43,635
to my second-born
and favorite son Moe.

631
00:39:45,240 --> 00:39:46,560
<i>That's sweet.</i>

632
00:39:46,640 --> 00:39:49,155
<i>He must have
really loved that boy.</i>

633
00:39:49,280 --> 00:39:50,873
Anyway, that's it.

634
00:39:50,960 --> 00:39:54,237
Once again,
I'm sorry for your loss.

635
00:39:54,320 --> 00:39:57,279
If you have any questions,
please don't hesitate to call me.

636
00:40:01,120 --> 00:40:05,558
Well, like I said, Mrs. Hess, 
we're checking some things on our end,

637
00:40:05,640 --> 00:40:07,074
but if there's anything
you could tell us

638
00:40:07,160 --> 00:40:08,435
about your husband's business...

639
00:40:08,520 --> 00:40:10,193
I appreciate the visit, Chief,

640
00:40:10,280 --> 00:40:13,193
but Mrs. Hess had no kind of 
involvement with Sam's business.

641
00:40:13,280 --> 00:40:15,237
Frankly, she's mystified.

642
00:40:15,320 --> 00:40:18,119
Her husband being a pillar of
the community and all.

643
00:40:18,200 --> 00:40:19,236
I mean, heck,

644
00:40:19,320 --> 00:40:22,154
voted Bemidji Businessman of the Year,
1996 and '98.

645
00:40:22,240 --> 00:40:23,515
Who... who was it?

646
00:40:23,600 --> 00:40:24,750
I'll tell you there.

647
00:40:24,840 --> 00:40:26,354
Yeah.

648
00:40:26,440 --> 00:40:28,591
Like I said, it's a puzzler.

649
00:40:28,680 --> 00:40:30,558
'Course, we both
know some of your boys

650
00:40:30,640 --> 00:40:32,438
have had run-ins with
the law in the past.

651
00:40:32,520 --> 00:40:34,591
Stolen merchandise
charges and the like.

652
00:40:34,680 --> 00:40:36,956
And, you know,
the Staties had that case

653
00:40:37,080 --> 00:40:38,480
as to maybe your
outfit's got ties

654
00:40:38,560 --> 00:40:41,792
to that crime
syndicate out of Fargo.

655
00:40:41,880 --> 00:40:44,270
You're gonna stand here...
Let me get this straight.

656
00:40:44,360 --> 00:40:45,430
You're gonna stand here

657
00:40:45,520 --> 00:40:48,240
and call the victim a criminal in 
front of his wife, his kids?

658
00:40:48,320 --> 00:40:50,277
Well, now, no one's calling
anyone a criminal.

659
00:40:50,360 --> 00:40:52,431
Just trying to figure
out what happened.

660
00:40:52,520 --> 00:40:56,036
Chief! 217! 217!

661
00:41:19,080 --> 00:41:20,560
What the heck?

662
00:41:36,360 --> 00:41:37,396
Heya, Lester.

663
00:41:37,480 --> 00:41:38,880
Hiya, Bo.

664
00:41:38,960 --> 00:41:41,429
Jeez, what happened
to your face there?

665
00:41:41,560 --> 00:41:43,313
You know that spot
near the fire station?

666
00:41:43,400 --> 00:41:44,516
Where they wash the trucks?

667
00:41:44,600 --> 00:41:45,590
Yep.

668
00:41:45,680 --> 00:41:48,718
Slipped on the ice.

669
00:41:48,800 --> 00:41:52,794
Say, Lester, I need you to
pull the file on Sam Hess.

670
00:41:53,920 --> 00:41:55,718
On who now?

671
00:41:55,800 --> 00:41:58,838
Sam Hess. You know, owns the truck
depot over on Winslow.

672
00:41:58,920 --> 00:42:00,957
You know, big fella.

673
00:42:01,080 --> 00:42:02,639
Yeah, well, he's dead.

674
00:42:04,520 --> 00:42:05,795
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

675
00:42:05,880 --> 00:42:07,917
Shame. It's a big policy.

676
00:42:08,680 --> 00:42:12,469
Murder, they're saying.
Stabbed to death is what I heard.

677
00:42:14,800 --> 00:42:16,234
You okay there, Lester?

678
00:42:17,120 --> 00:42:20,158
Sure.

679
00:42:20,240 --> 00:42:22,436
Sure... You know
I went to high school with him?

680
00:42:22,560 --> 00:42:23,550
You don't say.

681
00:42:23,640 --> 00:42:26,030
Well, anyway, I need you
to pull the policy on that.

682
00:42:26,120 --> 00:42:28,476
I have to get on the phone
with his wife later.

683
00:43:01,040 --> 00:43:02,030
Uh...

684
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:04,320
Did you...

685
00:43:05,840 --> 00:43:09,675
Jeez.
Did you really kill him? Sam?

686
00:43:09,760 --> 00:43:11,911
Oh, my God.

687
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:13,434
Is Sam dead?

688
00:43:15,480 --> 00:43:17,949
How do you feel about that?

689
00:43:18,040 --> 00:43:19,713
Well, I mean...

690
00:43:19,800 --> 00:43:23,635
of course, it's...
you know, a tragedy.

691
00:43:23,720 --> 00:43:24,949
Well, why'd you kill him then?

692
00:43:25,080 --> 00:43:26,514
Now hold on a second!

693
00:43:28,520 --> 00:43:29,670
I never--

694
00:43:29,760 --> 00:43:31,956
Well, actually, you did.

695
00:43:32,040 --> 00:43:33,599
Remember, yes or no?

696
00:43:33,680 --> 00:43:35,239
I never said yes.

697
00:43:35,320 --> 00:43:36,356
Didn't say no.

698
00:43:37,160 --> 00:43:40,278
No, that won't-- Come on.

699
00:43:40,360 --> 00:43:41,714
That...
In a court of law--

700
00:43:41,800 --> 00:43:43,439
Who said anything
about a court of law?

701
00:43:43,520 --> 00:43:44,510
Look, I just mean...

702
00:43:45,680 --> 00:43:47,399
I... Jeez.

703
00:43:49,400 --> 00:43:53,110
And he had a wife,
you know, and those boys.

704
00:43:53,200 --> 00:43:55,715
Lester, he put you in a 
barrel and rolled you on the road.

705
00:43:58,200 --> 00:44:03,320
Your problem is you spent your 
whole life thinking there are rules.

706
00:44:03,400 --> 00:44:05,596
There aren't.

707
00:44:05,680 --> 00:44:07,637
We used to be gorillas.

708
00:44:07,720 --> 00:44:10,952
All we had is what
we could take and defend.

709
00:44:11,040 --> 00:44:14,112
The truth is you're more of a man 
today than you were yesterday.

710
00:44:15,680 --> 00:44:17,319
How do you figure?

711
00:44:18,080 --> 00:44:21,551
It's a red tide, Lester,
this life of ours.

712
00:44:24,760 --> 00:44:26,831
The shit they make us eat...

713
00:44:28,040 --> 00:44:29,679
day after day,

714
00:44:29,760 --> 00:44:34,073
the boss, the wife,
et cetera, wearing us down.

715
00:44:34,160 --> 00:44:36,516
If you don't stand up to it,

716
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:41,356
let 'em know you're still an 
ape deep down, where it counts.

717
00:44:41,440 --> 00:44:44,035
You're just gonna
get washed away.

718
00:44:56,320 --> 00:44:59,791
Phone call, Chief.
It's the wife.

719
00:45:02,720 --> 00:45:03,870
Hey, hon.
<i>White.</i>

720
00:45:03,960 --> 00:45:05,519
White, what?

721
00:45:05,640 --> 00:45:08,314
I decided we're gonna
paint the nursery white.

722
00:45:08,400 --> 00:45:09,436
<i>It's already white.</i>

723
00:45:09,560 --> 00:45:13,315
Well...
I want to paint it again.

724
00:45:13,400 --> 00:45:16,313
The baby's room should have a new coat,
don't you think?

725
00:45:16,440 --> 00:45:17,920
I do.

726
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:19,116
Any particular shade?

727
00:45:19,200 --> 00:45:20,714
What do you mean?

728
00:45:20,800 --> 00:45:23,838
Well, you got your
bright white, your snow white...

729
00:45:23,920 --> 00:45:25,320
Eggshell.

730
00:45:27,840 --> 00:45:29,877
Right, there's eggshell.

731
00:45:29,960 --> 00:45:32,156
Oh. I hadn't thought of that.

732
00:45:32,240 --> 00:45:33,230
<i>I'll tell you what.</i>

733
00:45:33,320 --> 00:45:34,310
<i>Why don't I stop
by the hardware</i>

734
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:35,390
<i>and pick up some
different shades</i>

735
00:45:35,480 --> 00:45:36,516
and we'll figure
it out tonight?

736
00:45:36,600 --> 00:45:38,319
We're having a baby, Vern.

737
00:45:38,400 --> 00:45:40,039
<i>That's true.</i>

738
00:45:40,120 --> 00:45:42,999
No, I mean it's
finally sinking in.

739
00:45:43,080 --> 00:45:44,070
We're gonna have a baby.

740
00:45:44,160 --> 00:45:46,914
I can't wait.

741
00:45:47,000 --> 00:45:48,673
I'll see you soon.

742
00:45:53,840 --> 00:45:55,240
Is there anything else
you need there?

743
00:45:56,000 --> 00:45:57,957
Nope, I'm good.

744
00:46:02,880 --> 00:46:05,759
<i>Come in, Chief.</i>

745
00:46:05,840 --> 00:46:07,240
This is Vern. Go ahead.

746
00:46:07,320 --> 00:46:08,595
<i>Chief,
I'm over at the hospital.</i>

747
00:46:08,680 --> 00:46:10,672
<i>I was checking on
the Hess boy and--</i>

748
00:46:10,760 --> 00:46:11,796
How is he?

749
00:46:11,880 --> 00:46:14,998
<i>You know, broken collarbone.
Got his bell rung pretty good.</i>

750
00:46:16,160 --> 00:46:17,435
That's a shame.
<i>Yeah.</i>

751
00:46:17,520 --> 00:46:20,433
Hey, so I got to
talking to Sue Roundtree

752
00:46:20,520 --> 00:46:22,910
and I asked her if they 
had any head injuries lately,

753
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:25,117
you know, my theory about
the driver and the wreck,

754
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:27,556
and she says they did...
yesterday.

755
00:46:27,680 --> 00:46:30,832
<i>Real peculiar fella, she says.
Real intense.</i>

756
00:46:30,920 --> 00:46:32,115
<i>And here's where
it gets interesting.</i>

757
00:46:32,200 --> 00:46:34,112
'Cause she says the fella with
the head injury

758
00:46:34,200 --> 00:46:37,034
was talking to another fella
about Sam Hess.

759
00:46:38,080 --> 00:46:39,480
Yeah?
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

760
00:46:39,560 --> 00:46:41,472
Says the two was
thick as thieves.

761
00:46:41,560 --> 00:46:43,472
So suddenly I'm thinking
maybe these two cases,

762
00:46:43,560 --> 00:46:44,789
maybe they're connected, huh?

763
00:46:45,600 --> 00:46:47,592
Could be.

764
00:46:47,680 --> 00:46:49,717
She say who
the other fella was?

765
00:46:49,800 --> 00:46:51,996
<i>Lester Nygaard.</i>

766
00:46:52,120 --> 00:46:53,110
Really?

767
00:46:53,920 --> 00:46:54,910
You know him?

768
00:46:55,040 --> 00:46:56,269
<i>Sure, I know Lester.</i>

769
00:46:57,000 --> 00:46:59,151
Sells insurance
over at Bo's shop.

770
00:46:59,240 --> 00:47:01,277
Yeah, yeah, I called over
and they're closed,

771
00:47:01,360 --> 00:47:04,000
so I was gonna go
by Lester's place.

772
00:47:04,080 --> 00:47:06,037
<i>No, I know Lester.
I'll do it.</i>

773
00:47:06,920 --> 00:47:09,196
You call it a day.
Good work.

774
00:47:25,560 --> 00:47:27,313
Lester?

775
00:47:27,400 --> 00:47:29,710
In the basement.

776
00:47:40,760 --> 00:47:43,036
Whatcha doing, hon?

777
00:47:43,120 --> 00:47:46,192
I'm... trying to
fix the darn thing.

778
00:47:46,280 --> 00:47:49,159
It looks like
the motor mount broke.

779
00:47:50,240 --> 00:47:52,038
You sure you know
what you're doing?

780
00:47:52,120 --> 00:47:54,919
It seems pretty
straightforward.

781
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:56,992
So, you want to
give her a try?

782
00:47:57,080 --> 00:47:58,958
